Quality Ingredients: Using a high-quality wine and stock is crucial for a sauce with depth and complexity.

directions.Direction: Make Pesto Sauce:
Toast the Pine Nuts:
In a dry skillet over medium heat, toast the pine nuts until they are golden brown, stirring frequently to prevent burning. This should take about 3-5 minutes. Set aside to cool.
Prepare the Basil:
In a dry skillet over medium heat, toast the pine nuts until they are golden brown, stirring frequently to prevent burning. This should take about 3-5 minutes. Set aside to cool.
Put basil leaves into an ice bath for about 5 min (it helps to keep them green bright color) Wash and thoroughly dry the basil leaves.
Pound the Garlic and Salt:
In a mortar, add the garlic cloves and a pinch of salt. Use the pestle to pound them into a smooth paste. The salt will help to break down the garlic.
Add the Pine Nuts:
Add the toasted pine nuts to the mortar. Pound them into the garlic paste until you achieve a somewhat smooth consistency.
Incorporate the Basil:

Add the basil leaves a handful at a time. Use a circular motion with the pestle to crush the basil against the sides of the mortar. Continue adding and pounding until all the basil leaves are broken down into a rough paste.
Mix in the Cheese:
Add the grated Parmesan and Pecorino cheese to the mortar and mix it thoroughly with the basil paste using the pestle.
Add the Olive Oil:
Gradually add the extra virgin olive oil to the mixture, a little at a time, while continuing to stir and mix with the pestle. This helps to emulsify the pesto, making it smooth and creamy.
Season and Adjust:
Taste the pesto and season with salt and freshly ground black pepper to your liking. Add the lemon juice if using, and mix again.
Serve or Store:

Use immediately, or transfer the pesto to an airtight container. If storing, drizzle a thin layer of olive oil on top of the pesto to prevent it from oxidizing and turning brown. Store in the refrigerator for up to a week, or freeze for longer storage.

Add the basil leaves in batches. Pulse the hand blender to break down the leaves, maintaining control to prevent over-processing. This method helps to retain a nice texture.

Be cautious not to run the hand blender continuously for too long, as it can heat up and alter the flavor of the pesto. Short pulses work best.
